<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-03-24T18:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-03-24T18:36:00-05:00" n="1133" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1133">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">774.5/3–2453: Telegram</note>
                            <head>No. 1133<lb/><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United
                                        Kingdom</gloss></hi><note n="1" xml:id="d1133fn1">Repeated
                                    priority to Cairo as telegram 1885. Drafted and approved by
                                        <persName corresp="#p_BHA1">Byroade</persName>.</note></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">top
                                        secret<lb/>priority</hi></seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-03-24T18:36:00-05:00">March 24, 1953—6:36
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>6343. For your information US views on British note contained in
                                    <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 1883 presented to
                                British in writing inform contained above <gloss target="#t_reftel1">reftel</gloss> in three paragraphs in middle of message
                                immediately subsequent to the phrase “End Verbatim Text.” British
                                were not shown copy of personal message from the President to
                                    <persName corresp="#p_NGM1">Naguib</persName> but were given
                                orally summary of points it covered. We felt it improper show text
                                to British and were fearful of leak that personal confidential <pb facs="0335" n="2037" xml:id="pg_2037"/> message to head of third
                                State had been coordinated with them.</p>
                            <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_DJF2"><hi rend="strong"><hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi></hi></persName></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>